1. Objectives and Goals

The primary objective of this assignment is to illustrate that you understand the final steps of bulk-RNAseq data processing as it pertains to data clean up, modelling and differential gene expression analysis. By the end of this lecture and assignment you should be able to:

  • generate results and volcano plots of differentially expressed genes between different biological groups
  • generate heatmaps of expression on normalized dataset
  • perform enrichment and pathway analysis
  • create visuals to illustrate enrichment and pathway analysis results

3.1 Volcano Plot

  1. Perform the following tasks to create a volcano plot of your data:
  1. Read in your csv differential expression results file and store it in a variable.
  2. create a column in your differential expression results data frame called -log10FDR and calculate the -log10FDR values
  3. create a column in your differential expression results data frame called gene and have it list all the gene names
  4. create a volcano plot of log2(foldChange) on the x-axis and negLog10FDR on the y-axis. Create a horizontal line that is equal to a neglog10(FDR) to neglog10(0.10), and 2 vertical lines, one where log2(FC) == 1 and one where log2(FC) == -1 and add labels to all genes that have an adjust p-value of less than 0.10.

## D
ggplot(DEdataf, aes(x = log2FoldChange, y = negLog10FDR)) +
      geom_point() +
      geom_vline(xintercept=c(-1, 1), col="red") +
      geom_hline(yintercept= (-1) * log10(0.10), col="red") +
      geom_text_repel(data=subset(DEdataf, padj < 0.10), aes(label = gene))

The volcano plot will look like the opposite because the denominator in the differential expression object was the opposite of ours, so the results will look mirrored. This only changes the directionality of the change, not the actual interpretations. For this reason, they are not really different.
